VALUES
(20, 26, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'He that hateth dissembleth with his lips,', 0, 41, 'connection', 'Connection to Matthew 15:18', 'This verse parallels Matthew 15:18, which states, ''But what comes out of the mouth proceeds from the heart, and this defiles a person.'' Both verses emphasize that what is spoken reflects inner intentions and attitudes. Understanding this connection helps illuminate the seriousness of deceitful speech as a manifestation of a corrupt heart.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 15:18", "description": "Jesus teaches about the heart''s role in speech."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 26, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'dissembleth with his lips,', 15, 41, 'greek', 'Greek Insight on ''Dissembleth''', 'The Hebrew word for ''dissembleth'' in this context is חָנֵף (ḥāneph, H2611) - deceitful, hypocritical. This term indicates not just lying but a deeper sense of betrayal against trust. Recognizing this adds a layer of understanding to the gravity of misleading speech in relationships.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2611", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 26, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'layeth up deceit within him;', 46, 74, 'theology', 'The Nature of Deceit', 'This passage suggests that deceit is a serious spiritual issue, as it reflects the condition of one''s heart. Many scholars believe that deceit is not merely a social failing but a spiritual condition that can lead to greater sin. This highlights the need for self-examination and integrity in one''s speech and motives.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Proverbs 12:22", "description": "Commentary notes on integrity vs. deceit."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 26, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'He that hateth dissembleth with his lips,', 0, 41, 'question', 'Reflecting on Hatred and Deceit', 'In what ways might I be deceiving myself or others in my speech? How does this verse challenge me to confront any hidden animosities and ensure my words align with truth and love?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 26, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'When he speaketh fair, believe him not:', 0, 39, 'connection', 'Caution Against Deception', 'This phrase echoes the warning found in Jeremiah 9:8, which states, ''Their tongue is as an arrow shot out; it speaketh deceit...'' Both verses emphasize the danger of trusting smooth words that may conceal malevolent intentions. This highlights a biblical theme of discernment regarding the sincerity of speech.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Jeremiah 9:8", "description": "A warning about deceitful speech"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 26, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'for there are seven abominations in his heart.', 40, 86, 'theology', 'Nature of the Heart', 'Many scholars believe that the ''seven abominations'' represent a completeness of sinfulness, echoing the biblical understanding of the heart''s corruption (Jeremiah 17:9). This suggests that human nature is inherently flawed and prone to deceit, underscoring the need for divine regeneration and transformation.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the nature of the heart and its inclinations"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 26, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'believe him not:', 23, 39, 'question', 'Trust and Discernment', 'What criteria do you use to determine if someone is being truthful? Reflecting on this verse, how can you cultivate greater discernment in your relationships, especially when confronted with seemingly kind words?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 26, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'When he speaketh fair, believe him not:', 0, 39, 'greek', 'Understanding ''speaketh fair''', 'The phrase ''speaketh fair'' translates to the Hebrew term ''חָלָק'' (chalak, H2519) - smooth, flattering, or deceitful speech. This term indicates a polished or deceptive manner of speaking that can mask true intentions, reinforcing the necessity of spiritual discernment in communication.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2519", "description": "Hebrew term related to smooth or flattering speech"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 26, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'Whose hatred is covered by deceit', 0, 33, 'connection', 'Hidden Hatred in Scripture', 'This phrase connects to James 3:14-16, which discusses how bitter envy and selfish ambition can lead to disorder and evil practices. The parallel illustrates that hidden motivations, like hatred masked by deceit, ultimately reveal a person''s true character and lead to chaos. Understanding this connection encourages believers to examine their own hearts for hidden sins.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 3:14-16", "description": "Discusses the consequences of hidden bitterness and envy."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 26, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'his wickedness shall be shewed before the whole congregation', 35, 95, 'theology', 'Public Judgment and Accountability', 'This passage suggests that there is a divine principle of accountability, where hidden wickedness will eventually come to light. Many scholars believe that this reflects God’s justice, as seen in Luke 12:2, which states that nothing is covered that will not be revealed. This underscores the importance of integrity and the idea that God sees all actions, fostering a sense of moral responsibility.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Luke 12:2", "description": "Affirms the theme of hidden things being revealed."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 26, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'his wickedness shall be shewed before the whole congregation', 35, 95, 'question', 'Impact of Hidden Sin', 'What does it mean for our personal sins or hidden resentments to be exposed in a communal setting? How can this awareness influence our interactions with others and the way we handle conflicts within our community?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 26, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'Whoso diggeth a pit shall fall therein:', 0, 39, 'connection', 'Consequences of Deceit', 'This phrase echoes the principle found in Galatians 6:7, which states, ''For whatsoever a man soweth, that shall he also reap.'' Both verses highlight the inevitable consequences of one''s actions, especially when those actions are harmful or deceitful. The connection underscores a universal moral truth: those who plot harm for others often end up suffering the repercussions themselves.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Galatians 6:7", "description": "Emphasizes the principle of reaping what you sow."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 26, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'and he that rolleth a stone, it will return upon him.', 40, 93, 'theology', 'Divine Justice', 'This passage suggests that God''s justice is inescapable. Many scholars believe that the imagery of the stone returning signifies that attempts to harm others will ultimately backfire. This aligns with the broader biblical theme of divine retribution, where God ensures that evil deeds are not left unpunished, reinforcing the moral order of the universe.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the theme of divine justice and retribution."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 26, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'Whoso diggeth a pit shall fall therein:', 0, 39, 'question', 'Self-Inflicted Harm', 'In what ways might we unknowingly set traps for ourselves through our actions or words? Reflecting on this truth can lead to deeper self-examination and awareness of how our intentions may lead to unintended consequences, prompting us to act with greater integrity and mindfulness.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 26, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'and he that rolleth a stone, it will return upon him.', 40, 93, 'greek', 'Returning Consequences', 'ἀποδοθήσεται (apodothēsontai, G591) - it will be returned. This term emphasizes the concept of recompense, indicating that actions, particularly harmful ones, will come back to the actor. Understanding this term deepens the meaning of the warning against deceitful behavior and reinforces the notion of accountability.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G591", "description": "Refers to being given back or returned."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 26, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'A lying tongue hateth those that are afflicted by it;', 0, 53, 'connection', 'Lying Tongue in Scripture', 'This phrase echoes James 3:6, which warns that the tongue can set the course of one''s life on fire. The connection highlights the destructive nature of deceit and reveals the deep-seated hatred that lies can foster, particularly towards those who are vulnerable. It encourages readers to consider the impact of their words on others.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 3:6", "description": "Illustrates the destructive power of the tongue."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 26, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'and a flattering mouth worketh ruin.', 54, 90, 'theology', 'Flattery''s Consequences', 'Many scholars believe that this verse warns against the dangers of flattery, which can lead to moral ruin. Theologically, it reflects the biblical principle that genuine wisdom and integrity are rooted in truthfulness, while flattery undermines authentic relationships and can lead individuals astray. This connects to Proverbs 29:5, where flattery is portrayed as deceptive.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 29:5", "description": "Shows the deceptive nature of flattery."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 26, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'A lying tongue hateth those that are afflicted by it;', 0, 53, 'question', 'Impact of Our Words', 'How does recognizing the harm caused by a lying tongue change your approach to communication? Reflect on specific instances where honesty—or the lack thereof—has affected relationships in your life.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 26, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'and a flattering mouth worketh ruin.', 54, 90, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Flattering''', 'κολακεία (kolakeia, G2851) - flattery, smooth talk. This term suggests an insincere praise meant to manipulate or deceive, emphasizing the danger of insincerity in speech and its potential to lead to destruction.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2851", "description": "Defines the Greek term for flattery."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'Boast not thyself of to morrow;', 0, 31, 'connection', 'Humility in Planning', 'This phrase resonates with James 4:13-15, which warns against boasting about future plans without acknowledging God''s will. Both passages emphasize the uncertainty of tomorrow and the importance of humility. They remind believers to submit their plans to God, recognizing His sovereignty over time and events.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 4:13-15", "description": "James cautions against presuming on the future without recognizing God''s control."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'for thou knowest not what a day may bring forth.', 32, 80, 'theology', 'The Uncertainty of Life', 'This passage suggests the theological concept of divine providence, where God governs the future and the events of each day. Many scholars believe that recognizing our lack of control fosters reliance on God. By acknowledging that we do not know what a day may bring, we are encouraged to live with faith and trust in His plan.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'Boast not thyself of to morrow;', 0, 31, 'question', 'Reflecting on Tomorrow', 'What does it mean for your daily life to not boast about tomorrow, especially in your plans and aspirations? How can this understanding influence your approach to making decisions and setting goals?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'Let another man praise thee, and not thine own mouth; a stranger, and not thine own lips.', 0, 89, 'connection', 'Self-Praise in Scripture', 'This verse aligns closely with Proverbs 25:6-7, which advises against self-promotion. Both passages emphasize humility and the value of external validation over self-aggrandizement. This reinforces the biblical principle that true honor comes from others, not from self-assertion.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 25:6-7", "description": "Admonition against self-exaltation."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'Let another man praise thee, and not thine own mouth; a stranger, and not thine own lips.', 0, 89, 'theology', 'Value of Humility', 'Many scholars believe this passage underscores the biblical teaching on humility, suggesting that self-promotion is contrary to the character of Christ, who exemplified servant leadership. This aligns with Philippians 2:3, which encourages believers to value others above themselves.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Philippians 2:3", "description": "Encouragement to practice humility."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'Let another man praise thee, and not thine own mouth; a stranger, and not thine own lips.', 0, 89, 'question', 'Reflecting on Praise', 'What does it reveal about our character when we seek to uplift ourselves rather than allowing others to recognize our worth? How might this understanding change our interactions and relationships?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'Let another man praise thee, and not thine own mouth; a stranger, and not thine own lips.', 0, 89, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Praise''', 'ἐπαινεῖν (epainein, G1867) - to commend, praise. This term highlights the importance of receiving commendation from others, which is a recurring theme in wisdom literature regarding the value of community recognition over self-promotion.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G1867", "description": "Greek term for ''to praise.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'A stone is heavy, and the sand weighty;', 0, 39, 'connection', 'Weight of Burdens', 'The imagery of heavy stones and weighty sand evokes the burdens we carry in life. In Jeremiah 17:9, we see that the heart can also be a weighty burden, leading us astray. This connection highlights the concept that while physical burdens are tangible, emotional and spiritual burdens can be even heavier if not addressed.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Jeremiah 17:9", "description": "The heart is deceitful and burdensome."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'but a fool’s wrath is heavier than them both.', 40, 85, 'theology', 'Consequences of Wrath', 'This passage suggests that a fool''s wrath brings about significant consequences, emphasizing the importance of self-control. Many scholars believe that anger, when unchecked, leads to destruction, as noted in James 1:20, which states, ''for the anger of man does not produce the righteousness of God.'' This highlights the need for wisdom in managing our emotions.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 1:20", "description": "Anger does not produce righteousness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'A stone is heavy, and the sand weighty;', 0, 39, 'question', 'Understanding Weighty Burdens', 'What does it reveal about human nature that emotional burdens, like a fool''s wrath, can surpass the weight of physical objects? How should this understanding influence our interactions with others, especially when faced with anger or frustration?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'but a fool’s wrath is heavier than them both.', 40, 85, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Fool''', 'נָבָל (naval, H5036) - fool, senseless person. The Hebrew term used here emphasizes a lack of understanding and moral judgment. This insight into the meaning of ''fool'' enriches our comprehension of the consequences of unchecked wrath, revealing that it stems from a deeper foolishness.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5036", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for fool."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'Wrath is cruel, and anger is outrageous;', 0, 40, 'connection', 'Cross-Reference to James', 'James 1:20 states, ''For the wrath of man worketh not the righteousness of God.'' This connection highlights that human wrath is inherently flawed and counterproductive to divine righteousness, reinforcing the idea that while wrath may feel justified, it often leads to destructive outcomes.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 1:20", "description": "This verse emphasizes the futility of human anger."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'but who is able to stand before envy?', 41, 78, 'theology', 'The Nature of Envy', 'This passage suggests that envy can lead to profound relational damage and moral failure. Many scholars believe that envy is not just a feeling but a catalyst for sin, as seen in the story of Cain and Abel (Genesis 4:3-8), where envy resulted in violence. It emphasizes the need for vigilance against such emotions.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis 4:3-8", "description": "The story of Cain and Abel illustrates the destructive nature of envy."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'Wrath is cruel, and anger is outrageous;', 0, 40, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Wrath''', 'חֵמָה (chemah, H2534) - heat, fury, rage. This Hebrew word indicates not just a passing anger but a deep-seated and intense emotional response. Understanding its weight helps in comprehending the seriousness of allowing such emotions to dictate our actions.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2534", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for wrath."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'but who is able to stand before envy?', 41, 78, 'question', 'Reflect on Envy''s Impact', 'In what ways has envy influenced your decisions or relationships? How might recognizing its power help you to confront and mitigate its effects in your life?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'Open rebuke is better than secret love.', 0, 39, 'connection', 'Scriptural Affirmation', 'This verse highlights the value of honest communication in relationships. Cross-referencing Galatians 6:1, where Paul encourages believers to restore those caught in sin gently, underscores the importance of accountability and truth in love. Moreover, Proverbs 28:23 states, ''He who rebukes a man will afterward find more favor than he who flatters with the tongue,'' affirming the idea that open rebuke leads to deeper trust and respect.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Galatians 6:1", "description": "Encourages believers to restore others gently."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 28:23", "description": "Highlights the favor found in honest rebuke."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'Open rebuke is better than secret love.', 0, 39, 'theology', 'The Nature of Love', 'This passage suggests that genuine love is often expressed through truth-telling, even when it is uncomfortable. Many scholars believe that true love includes the willingness to confront and correct, as exemplified by God''s relationship with His people. This aligns with the understanding that love is not just affectionate feelings but also a commitment to the well-being of others, as seen in 1 Corinthians 13:6, which states that love ''rejoices in the truth.''', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'Open rebuke is better than secret love.', 0, 39, 'question', 'Reflecting on Rebuke', 'What does it mean for you to receive open rebuke in your life? How can you discern when to offer rebuke to others in a loving and constructive manner? Consider how this balance of honesty and love plays out in your relationships.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'Open rebuke is better than secret love.', 0, 39, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Rebuke''', 'נָכָה (nakah, H5221) - to strike, to hit, to chastise. This Hebrew term emphasizes the action of correction inherent in rebuke. Unlike mere criticism, ''nakah'' conveys a purposeful intent to improve and guide the recipient towards better choices, reflecting the constructive nature of true loving relationships.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5221", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term for rebuke."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'Faithful are the wounds of a friend', 0, 35, 'connection', 'Friendship''s True Nature', 'This phrase connects powerfully with Proverbs 17:17, which states, ''A friend loves at all times, and a brother is born for adversity.'' Both verses highlight the essential role of true friends in our lives, emphasizing that genuine love often involves difficult truths. The connection encourages us to embrace constructive criticism from friends rather than seeking comfort from those who may not have our best interests at heart.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 17:17", "description": "Highlights the nature of true friendship."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'but the kisses of an enemy are deceitful.', 37, 78, 'theology', 'Discernment in Relationships', 'This passage suggests that not all expressions of affection are genuine. Many scholars believe this highlights the importance of discernment in our relationships, distinguishing between those who truly care for us and those who may have ulterior motives. This aligns with teachings in the New Testament, such as Matthew 7:15, which warns about false prophets and encourages vigilance in recognizing true intentions.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 7:15", "description": "Warns of false appearances in relationships."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'Faithful are the wounds of a friend', 0, 35, 'question', 'Understanding Constructive Criticism', 'What does it mean for a wound to be faithful? In what ways can we learn to appreciate the honest feedback from friends, even when it hurts? Reflecting on this can help us recognize the value of authenticity in our friendships and how it shapes our character.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'the kisses of an enemy are deceitful.', 41, 78, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Deceitful''', 'ἄπιστος (apistos, G570) - unfaithful, untrustworthy. This Greek term underlines the nature of deceit in relationships. It emphasizes that appearances can be misleading and that one must be cautious in discerning true loyalty versus betrayal. This insight invites deeper reflection on how we evaluate our relationships.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G570", "description": "Indicates the nature of untrustworthiness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'The full soul loatheth an honeycomb;', 0, 36, 'connection', 'Comparison of Satisfaction', 'This phrase can be connected to Proverbs 30:15-16, which also discusses insatiable desires. The comparison highlights how abundance can lead to a lack of appreciation for what is otherwise sweet and desirable. Understanding the context of fullness versus hunger deepens the insight into human nature and our propensity to take blessings for granted.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 30:15-16", "description": "Explores the nature of insatiable desires."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'but to the hungry soul every bitter thing is sweet.', 37, 88, 'theology', 'Spiritual Hunger', 'Many scholars believe this passage illustrates the concept of spiritual hunger and its significance in the Christian life. Just as a physical hunger can make even unpalatable food desirable, so too can a deep spiritual longing lead individuals to seek and find value in what might initially seem unpleasant. This aligns with Jesus'' teaching in Matthew 5:6 about those who hunger and thirst for righteousness.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew 5:6", "description": "Jesus emphasizes the blessing of those who seek righteousness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'The full soul loatheth an honeycomb;', 0, 36, 'question', 'Value of Contentment', 'What does this verse reveal about the dangers of complacency and the value of contentment? How can we cultivate a spirit of gratitude that recognizes the sweetness of our blessings, even in times of abundance?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'but to the hungry soul every bitter thing is sweet.', 37, 88, 'greek', 'Key Term Analysis', 'πείνα (peina, G3983) - hunger, desire for food. This term emphasizes the state of longing and need, both physically and spiritually. Understanding this concept sheds light on how our deepest needs can alter our perceptions and desires.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G3983", "description": "Strong''s number for ''hunger''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'As a bird that wandereth from her nest', 0, 38, 'connection', 'Parable of the Lost', 'This phrase resonates with the parable of the lost sheep in Luke 15:4-7, where a shepherd leaves the ninety-nine to find the one that is lost. It emphasizes the value of being in one''s rightful place and the dangers of straying away. Just as the bird is vulnerable when away from its nest, so too is a person who wanders from their designated role or community.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Luke 15:4-7", "description": "The parable highlighting the importance of staying within one''s community."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'so is a man that wandereth from his place', 40, 81, 'theology', 'The Importance of Stability', 'This passage suggests the theological concept of belonging and stability within God''s created order. Many scholars believe that a man''s ''place'' references not only physical location but also spiritual and relational positioning within the community. Stability is seen as a divine principle, as evidenced in Ephesians 4:16, where the body of Christ is called to work together in unity.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Ephesians 4:16", "description": "Discussion on the unity and interdependence in the body of Christ."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'As a bird that wandereth from her nest', 0, 38, 'question', 'Reflecting on Wanderings', 'What does it mean for you personally to ''wander from your place''? In what areas of your life might you feel out of alignment with where God has called you to be? Reflecting on this can lead to deeper understanding of your spiritual and relational commitments.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 27, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'Ointment and perfume rejoice the heart:', 0, 39, 'connection', 'Joy in Relationships', 'This phrase parallels Psalm 104:15, which speaks of oil that makes the heart glad. Both verses highlight how sensory experiences can evoke joy, emphasizing the importance of relationships that bring happiness and comfort. Just as ointment and perfume are used to enhance physical pleasure, so too can the counsel of friends elevate our emotional and spiritual well-being.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 104:15", "description": "This verse speaks of oil that brings joy to the heart, highlighting the connection between sensory pleasure and emotional well-being."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');